Title : Seven Deadly Sins: My Pursuit of Lance Armstrong
Text : {{italic title}}
'''''Seven Deadly Sins: My Pursuit of Lance Armstrong''''' is a sports book written by ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' journalist [[David Walsh (journalist)|David Walsh]], which released on December 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|first=Samuel|last=Luckhurst|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/12/21/david-walsh-lance-armstrong_n_2345484.html|title=David Walsh On His Pursuit Of Lance Armstrong|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=April 26, 2014|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> In the book, Walsh writes about his 13-year fight to bring out the truth behind American cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]]'s seven [[Tour de France]] wins, i.e. that Armstrong had used banned substances. Walsh was vindicated when Armstrong was stripped of all seven of his Tour titles and banned from sport for life on October 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Walsh|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/the_bonus/10/22/david-walsh-lance-armstrong/|title=Covering Lance Armstrong was a wild ride, but the truth came out|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=April 26, 2014|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> Armstrong's seven Tour wins are told to be his "seven deadly sins".

Armstrong confessed to doping in an interview with [[Oprah Winfrey]] in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rory|last=Carroll|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jan/18/lance-armstrong-admits-doping-oprah-winfrey|title=Lance Armstrong admits doping in Oprah Winfrey interview |date=Jan 18, 2013|accessdate=June 6, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> The 2015 movie ''[[The Program (2015 film)|The Program]]'' is based on the book. [[Chris O'Dowd]] and [[Ben Foster]] star as Walsh and Armstrong, respectively. The movie earned $3.3 million worldwide.<ref name="BoxOffice">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=theprogram2015.htm | title=The Program (2016)| work=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>

